Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887100008&r=1&w=2">change in host table</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837692300023&r=1&w=2">Mark Crispin &lt;Crispin () SUMEX-AIM ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198505">1985-05-01 13:23:57</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426405&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426405&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Folks -

     I object vehemently to the way in which the introduction of domain
names is being done to the NIC host table.  It introduces a "Flag Day"
in which there will be hosts which use the new names as the primary name
and other hosts which can't handle the new names at all.  My vehemence
is because there is a simple way out of this problem.

     The next NIC HOSTS.TXT file should NOT have the fully qualified
domain names as the primary name.  RATHER, it should have the fully
qualified domain names as NICKNAMES.  The idea here is that non-domain
sites using HOSTS.TXT will be able to parse the domain names but not
use them.

     SOON thereafter (a week or so), make the fully qualified domain
name be the primary name in HOSTS.TXT.

     The idea is to introduce a 1-week transition period for HOSTS.TXT
and have two milestones instead of just one.  This gives a week for
everybody to start handling these new names in the host table without
actually using them.

     PLEASE!!  No more "Flag Days"!  I am seriously worried about a
partition of the namespace happening between those who jump in and run
the new host table right away and those who want to "wait and see" (or
who, in one case, have their system programmer going away for the
weekend).  I believe my alternative is both technically feasible and
allows for a more graceful transition.

-- Mark --
